style="width:369pt;border-top-style:solid;border-top-width:1pt;border-top-color:#818181;border-left-style:solid;border-left-width:1pt;border-left-color:#818181;border-bottom-style:solid;border-bottom-width:1pt;border-bottom-color:#818181;border-right-style:solid;border-right-width:1pt;border-right-color:#818181"><p class="s11" style="padding-top: 1pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 10pt;text-align: left;">Warehouse Management System</p></td></tr></table><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p class="s9" style="padding-top: 5pt;padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><a name="bookmark0">NAME OF THE MICRO-SERVICE/PRODUCT – PROVIDER</a><a name="bookmark35">&zwnj;</a></p><h4 style="padding-top: 3pt;padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Crop Status Monitoring</h4><p style="padding-top: 3pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">This micro-service will deliver a number of EO derived indicators for crop status monitoring consisting of:</p><ul id="l1"><li data-list-text=""><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: -18pt;line-height: 11pt;text-align: left;">Crop Vegetation Indices (VΙs);</p></li><li data-list-text=""><p style="padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: -18pt;line-height: 11pt;text-align: left;">Crop Leaf Area Index (LAI);</p></li><li data-list-text=""><p style="padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: -18pt;line-height: 11pt;text-align: left;">Crop Nutrient Stress.</p><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">The service will further calculate differences between consecutive dates to ensure effective monitoring of the crop condition variability in both space and time. The system for the calculation and application of the VIs will be optimized with respect to crop types and phenological stages of the crops.</p><p style="padding-top: 3pt;padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">To ensure high temporal coverage of the data, the system will utilize data from different optical sensors, namely the Sentinel-2, Landsat 8 and MODIS.</p><p style="padding-top: 3pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">The provider - Participant of the Crop Status Monitoring Service is <b>AgroApps P.C. (AGA)</b>. The service is provided through a centralized integration RESTful API. The API interface encapsulates the complexity of satellite data management and decision algorithms offering an easy to integrate environment for the external clients.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p class="s13" style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark1">DESCRIPTION OF THE MICRO-SERVICE</a><a name="bookmark36">&zwnj;</a></p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">The <b>Crop Status Monitoring (CSM) Service</b>, is an earth observation crop monitoring module that exploits multispectral satellite data, and through the use of validated algorithms, provides crop monitoring products to the external client. The aim of the <b>CSM service </b>is to provide farmers with information on their crops’ health status, through a biophysical proxy, namely the NDVI and biophysical parameters (Leaf Area Index – LAI, Chlorophyll content – Chl, above ground crop biomass production). The CSM service multi-device application component (<b>web-based or mobile</b>) can help farmers identify anomalies in plant performance during the growing season, by comparing consecutive satellite images of high resolution (10 m or 20 m) depicting the status of their insured parcels.</p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">The <b>CSM Service </b>will provide crop growth information in parcel and sub parcel level and will enable farmers to keep an eye on their crops’ status <b>from emergence through harvest</b>. Local deviations of the calculated parameters could imply the occurrence of abiotic and/or biotic stress in crops. Indirectly, crop growth monitoring helps in delineating different management zones at sub-parcel level, that are otherwise invisible to the naked eye, for variable rate application of crop protection products (CPPs) or fertilizers. The crop monitoring data are crop specific for <b>wheat</b>, <b>maize</b>, <b>soybean</b>, <b>cotton </b>and <b>sunflower</b>.</p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">The NDVI anomaly for each registered crop will also be provided. The NDVI anomaly is calculated by comparing the average NDVI for a particular time period (8-day) and the average NDVI for the same time period over a specified number of years. NDVI anomaly product is calculated to characterize the health of vegetation compared to what is considered normal and is used as an indicator of drought or declining vegetation health.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 11pt;text-align: justify;">The procedure is described in the following steps:</p><ol id="l2"><li data-list-text="1."><p style="padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: -18pt;text-align: justify;">In the case of Sentinel imagery, the system communicates with the Copernicus Open Access Data Hub through the CDS-API in order to retrieve the corresponding Sentinel product ID and saves the results in an .xml file. Similarly, the same procedure is followed with other satellite data hubs (e.g. for Landsat-8 and MODIS). Based on the area of interest (AOI), date and cloudiness level thresholds, the CDS-API responds with a unique product ID that matches the search criteria and is the identifier for the targeted tile. The products are then located in an Amazon S3 bucket with “requester pays” permission.</p></li><li data-list-text="2."><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: -18pt;text-align: justify;">Once the satellite product is identified, a request is issued to Amazon S3 to acquire it, specifying optionally the bands to download. Data are acquired through the AWS API gateway in a programmatic way. A Python script is used for this task, modified to suit the needs of the service. Possessing the unique ID, the system proceeds to collect the necessary information layers from the EO providers.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p></li><li data-list-text="3."><p style="padding-top: 5pt;padding-left: 42pt;text-indent: -18pt;text-align: justify;">The primary raw satellite data are corrected for atmospheric and topographic effects, before masking. The analyzed following procedures are included in the workflow of the system.</p><ul id="l3"><li data-list-text=""><p class="s14" style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 69pt;text-indent: -18pt;text-align: justify;">Resampling and Layer Stack. <span class="p">After the data have been corrected, all spectral bands that are going to be imported into the database are Stacked together into one multiband image using GDAL. Optical Satellite layers come in different resolutions across the different spectral channels. This is a result of the different spectral range each band exhibits, and the reciprocal relation between band range and pixel resolution. However, a multi sized product cannot be further processed by raster algebra operators since pixels do not align one below the other. Therefore, the multi sized stack has to be resampled at the highest resolution, before any other processing takes place. In this step, all the 10 m (02-04 and 08) and 20 m (05-07 and 8A, 11, 12) of the S2 bands are merged together</span></p><p style="padding-left: 69pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 11pt;text-align: justify;">– with 20 m bands first being upsampled to 10 m resolution.</p></li><li data-list-text=""><p class="s14" style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 69pt;text-indent: -18pt;text-align: justify;">Data Quality Masking. <span class="p">Before the data can be imported into the database, it&#39;s very important to remove the abnormal values from it. Pixel reflectance values can be easily corrupted by various types of clouds or cloud shadows. In some cases it&#39;s very easy to detect these pixels, such as those that are covered by thick clouds. But it&#39;s very hard to distinguish pixels covered by cirrus clouds or thin clouds, even with visual inspection and let-alone with automatic detection. To this aim, the system applies a cloud masking technique.</span></p></li><li data-list-text=""><p class="s14" style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 69pt;text-indent: -18pt;text-align: justify;">Cropping the Area of Interest (AOI) and rejecting cloudy tiles. <span class="p">This step is primarily introduced to save memory if needed– for the cases where area of interest only falls into a small portion of the tile. That is why an additional step is performed – cropping the image to a specified polygon using GDAL utilities (gdalwarp with -cutline parameter).</span></p></li></ul></li><li data-list-text="4."><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: -18pt;text-align: justify;">Once the desired information is downloaded and after the processes of cloud masking and clipping (based on the requested area of interest), the system applies feature extraction algorithms and raster algebra operators according to the workflow of the preferred service. An online library of crop-specific algorithms is applied to the polygon of interest producing a set of georeferenced raster files.</p></li><li data-list-text="5."><p style="padding-top: 3pt;padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: -18pt;text-align: justify;">The processed EO data will be stored in Rasdaman and Geoserver databases. Geoserver will serve WMS for the purpose of data visualization, and Rasdaman’s API will be used for querying the data. Data is inserted into Rasdaman using an import script and a .json file with necessary parameters, such as input files paths, name of the collection where to insert the data, network address of service endpoint, storing options like tiling, band names and date-time extraction etc.</p></li></ol><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p class="s13" style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><a name="bookmark2">MICRO-Service: Crop Status Monitoring (CSM) / Products: Vegetation Indices –Biophysical Parameters – Web Mapping – Notifications – M2M choice – Export File choice</a><a name="bookmark37">&zwnj;</a></p><p style="padding-top: 3pt;padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">The service will provide:</p><ol id="l4"><li data-list-text="1."><p style="padding-top: 3pt;padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: -18pt;text-align: left;">alerts (push notifications) based on significant differences of crop status between consecutive dates;</p></li><li data-list-text="2."><p style="padding-left: 42pt;text-indent: -18pt;line-height: 11pt;text-align: left;">alerts (push notifications) of low or negative NDVI Anomaly values;</p></li><li data-list-text="3."><p style="padding-left: 42pt;text-indent: -18pt;line-height: 11pt;text-align: left;">maps of vegetation indices in sub-parcel level (pixel 10 m spatial resolution);</p></li><li data-list-text="4."><p style="padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: -18pt;line-height: 11pt;text-align: left;">maps of biophysical parameters in sub-parcel level (pixel 10 or 20 m spatial resolution);</p></li><li data-list-text="5."><p style="padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: -18pt;line-height: 11pt;text-align: left;">maps of NDVI Anomaly in sub-parcel level (pixel 250 m spatial resolution);</p></li><li data-list-text="6."><p style="padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: -18pt;line-height: 11pt;text-align: left;">M2M alternative to connect on variable rate fertilization systems through Apps on tractors;</p></li><li data-list-text="7."><p style="padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: -18pt;text-align: left;">Export .shp file to upload in automated variable rate fertilization systems through Apps on tractors.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">The provided <b>CSM service </b>addresses to different user segments:</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p></li></ol></li><li data-list-text=""><h4 style="padding-top: 5pt;padding-left: 42pt;text-indent: -18pt;text-align: justify;">farmers<span class="p">; by alerting farmers to possible stresses, through push notifications, they can address them early on and avoid yield damage that would arise if the situation was addressed later on;</span></h4></li><li data-list-text=""><h4 style="padding-left: 42pt;text-indent: -18pt;text-align: justify;">agricultural insurance companies<span class="p">; provides them with continuous information of their portfolio exposure in order to have an estimation of the maximum reimbursement cost, in the case of an event, and assist them in better pre- and after disaster-related decision-making;</span></h4></li><li data-list-text=""><h4 style="padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: -18pt;text-align: justify;">companies APIs<span class="p">, small and large scale </span>Agri-businesses<span class="p">; for improving the contract farming scheme and enabling sustainability advisers to continuously monitor the overall quality assurance of farmers’ (suppliers’) agricultural practices, in order to improve the environmental performance of products, throughout their life-cycle;</span></h4></li><li data-list-text=""><h4 style="padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: -18pt;text-align: justify;">policy makers<span class="p">; to assist policy makers in determining the performance of crops and crops’ varieties under different environments and base decisions on allocating and expanding crops and better planning crop suitability for future climate-resilience.</span></h4><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p class="s13" style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><a name="bookmark3">DEPENDENCIES OF THE MICRO-SERVICE FROM OTHER SERVICES</a><a name="bookmark38">&zwnj;</a></p><p style="padding-top: 3pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">The technological implementation of the satellite-based <b>CSM Service </b>of AgroApps P.C., needs to find a compromise between the following elements:</p><ol id="l5"><ol id="l6"><li data-list-text="1."><p style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 77pt;text-indent: -18pt;line-height: 11pt;text-align: left;">availability of ancillary input data, with minimal contribution from end-users;</p></li><li data-list-text="2."><p style="padding-left: 77pt;text-indent: -18pt;text-align: left;">elaboration and processing time, with minimum possible timelag between E.O. data acquisition date and information delivery to final users;</p></li></ol></ol><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p class="s13" style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><a name="bookmark5">EXTERNAL DEPENDENCIES/DATA ACQUISITION PLAN</a><a name="bookmark40">&zwnj;</a></p><ol id="l8"><li data-list-text="1."><h4 style="padding-top: 3pt;padding-left: 42pt;text-indent: -18pt;line-height: 11pt;text-align: justify;">Crop data<span class="p">.</span></h4><ul id="l9"><li data-list-text=""><p style="padding-left: Based on the imagery used, the appropriate bands and products will be assimilated for the calculation of the indices, the biophysical parameters will be crop specific, push notifications will be produced based on EO data processing and visualization (graphs, reports, widgets) will be populated based on the calculated values.</span></h4></li></ol><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">Any user of the SCM Service <b>can select a combination of input data originating from any Participant – Micro-Service provider</b>, active in the ATLAS Service Registry, or select to acquire them bundle from AgroApps P.C. (AGA).</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h2 style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark6">Micro-Service/ NDVI and Biophysical Parameters</a><a name="bookmark41">&zwnj;</a></h2><h3 style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark7">Role of the service/product</a><a name="bookmark42">&zwnj;</a></h3><p style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">Crop growth monitoring is the process of monitoring the crop status from emergence to harvest. Among the vegetation indices, NDVI is the one most often used for monitoring the environmental conditions (e.g. grassland status, land degradation, desertification, and drought) all over the world (<span style=" color: #0070C0;">Hassan et al., 2018</span>). In the CMS Service, NDVI is calculated and produced, along with the crop specific biophysical parameters LAI, chlorophyll concentration and above ground biomass. Biophysical parameters are crop specific for <b>wheat</b>, <b>maize</b>, <b>soybean</b>, <b>cotton </b>and <b>sunflower</b>. Monitoring of crop growth assists in early</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-top: 5pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">detection of stress factors due to water and nutrient deficiencies, as well as biotic stresses due to insect attacks and disease infestations.</p><h3 style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark8">Literature on the service/product</a><a name="bookmark43">&zwnj;</a></h3><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">Remote sensing can estimate crop parameters using regression/empirical models or simulations based on spectral vegetation indices (<span style=" color: #0070C0;">Gutierrez et al., 2010</span>). These parameters include LAI, biomass, chlorophyll concentration and others (<span style=" color: #0070C0;">Liu et al., 2012</span>; <span style=" color: #0070C0;">Nguy-Robertson et al., 2012</span>; <span style=" color: #0070C0;">Kross et al., 2015</span>). From the wide spectrum of Vegetation Indices available worldwide, LAI describes the area of leaves that cover a specific area of ground (unitless or m<span class="s16">2</span>/m<span class="s16">2</span>). Biomass corresponds to the produced mass of the dry aboveground biomass per unit of area that is produced by the crop. Chlorophyll content is the concentration of chlorophyll a and b per cm<span class="s16">2 </span>of leaf area. Crop biomass accumulation is calculated using Sentinel-2 imagery and is expressed in t/ha. Leaf Area Index (m<span class="s16">2</span>/m<span class="s16">2</span>) and chlorophyll content (g/m<span class="s16">2</span>) are calculated on Sentinel-2 imagery and are presented as per-parcel and sub-parcel level. The parameters are updated regularly, based on the temporal resolution and the condition (e.g. cloudiness) of the satellite imagery. All the above mentioned products of crop growth monitoring service are presented on maps through the multi-device application component (web-based or mobile).</p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">The CSM Service calculates chlorophyll content, LAI and Biomass using crop-specific, empirical models based on vegetation indices. The models were calibrated and validated against available in-situ data for wheat-barley (Spain), corn (Spain, Serbia), soybean (Serbia), sunflower (Spain, Serbia) and cotton (Greece) in order to identify optimal combinations of VIs-crops that provided the best fit between calculated and measured data.</p><h3 style="padding-top: 3pt;padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 12pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark9">Algorithm description</a><a name="bookmark10">&zwnj;</a><a name="bookmark44">&zwnj;</a><a name="bookmark45">&zwnj;</a></h3><p class="s17" style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 12pt;text-align: left;">NDVI</p><p style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">NDVI exploits the strength and the vitality of the vegetation on the earth&#39;s surface. The spectral signature of wholesome vegetation shows an abrupt rise of the reflection level at 0.7 µm, whereas land without vegetation, according to the type of surface, has a continuous linear course. So much more active the chlorophyll of the plants, so much bigger is the boost of the reflection level at the near infrared (0.78 - 1 µm). Apart from discriminating between vegetation and other objects, NDVI allows the characterization of the plant vigor (<span style=" color: #0070C0;">Rouse et al., 1974</span>). The index results from the following equation:</p><p class="s18" style="padding-left: 37pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 7pt;text-align: left;">NIR <span class="s19"></span>RED</p><p class="s18" style="padding-left: 7pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 13pt;text-align: left;">NDVI <span class="s19"></span></p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 1pt;text-align: left;"/><p class="s18" style="text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 13pt;text-align: left;">NIR <span class="s19"></span><span class="s20"> </span>RED</p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">where RED and NIR stand for the spectral reflectance measurements acquired in the red (visible) and near-infrared regions, respectively. These spectral reflectances are themselves ratios of the reflected over the incoming radiation in each spectral band individually, hence they take on values between 0.0 and 1.0. By design, the NDVI itself thus varies between -1.0 and 1.0.</p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark11">The NDVI is a measurement of the photosynthetic activity and is strongly correlated with density and vitality of the vegetation. The normalizing reduces topographic and atmospheric effects and enables the simultaneous examination of a wide area. The NDVI of an area containing a dense vegetation canopy will tend to positive values (0.3 to 0.8) while clouds and snow fields will be characterized by negative values of this index.</a><a name="bookmark46">&zwnj;</a></p><p class="s17" style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">Leaf Area Index (LAI)</p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">LAI is a key biophysical parameter of vegetation characterizing the structure and functioning of vegetation cover (<span style=" color: #0070C0;">Delegido et al., 2011</span>). It determines the size of the interface for exchange of energy (including radiation) and mass between the canopy and the atmosphere and also the transpiration, the interception and absorption rates of solar radiation by vegetation. LAI is a good metric to use in estimating crop vegetation status (<span style=" color: #0070C0;">Bobée et al., 2012</span>).</p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">In SCM Service, the crop-specific LAI is calculated for five crops, namely wheat, maize, cotton, soybean and sunflower. LAI values (in m<span class="s16">2</span>/m<span class="s16">2</span><a href="#bookmark47" class="s5">) are provided per pixel with a spatial resolution that depends on the VI used in the transfer function. LAI is calculated throughout the growing period from Sentinel-2 TOC multispectral data. The transfer function, the final spatial resolution and the spectral bands used for the calculation of this biophysical parameter are provided in Table </a>1.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: class="s11" style="padding-left: 11pt;padding-right: 10pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;">10 m</p></td></tr></table><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p class="s17" style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark12">Chlorophyll content</a><a name="bookmark48">&zwnj;</a></p><p style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">Chlorophyll content is one of the most important biophysical characteristics of crops. Chlorophyll can be related to photosynthetic capacity, thus, productivity, developmental stage, and canopy stresses (<span style=" color: #0070C0;">Ciganda et al., 2008). </span>Information on canopy chlorophyll or nitrogen content, in addition to properties like leaf area index, biomass and fraction of absorbed photosynthetically active radiation, is important in understanding plant functioning and status. Photosynthesis, occurring in so-called reaction centers containing chlorophyll, is one of the key processes in plants that is responsible for the energy and carbon balance (<span style=" color: #0070C0;">Clevers and Gitelson, 2013</span>). Chlorophyll content is highly correlated with canopy nitrogen content (<span style=" color: #0070C0;">Baret et al., 2007</span>). The Canopy Chlorophyll content is a physically sound quantity that represents the optical path in the canopy, where absorption by Chlorophyll dominates the radiometric signal. Thus, absorption by Chl provides the necessary link between remote sensing observations and canopy-state variables that are used as indicators of N status and photosynthetic capacity (<span style=" color: #0070C0;">Schlemmer et al, 2013</span>).</p><p style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">In the CMS Service, the crop-specific Chlorophyll content is calculated for five crops, namely wheat, maize, cotton, soybean and sunflower. Chlorophyll concentration values (in mg/cm<span class="s16">2</span><a href="#bookmark49" class="s5">) are provided per pixel with a spatial resolution that depends on the VI used in the transfer function. This biophysical parameter is calculated throughout the growing period from Sentinel-2 TOC multispectral data. The transfer functions, the final spatial resolution and the spectral bands used for the calculation of the biophysical parameter are provided in Table </a>2.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p class="s21" style="padding-left: 15pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;"><a name="bookmark49">Table 2. </a><span style=" color: #324750;">Transfer Functions for Chlorophyll class="s17" style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark13">Crop biomass accumulation</a><a name="bookmark50">&zwnj;</a></p><p style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">Above ground biomass is the crop main biophysical parameter and an indicator of crop growth. It is used as a quantitative characteristic of plant condition, for nutrient management and for predicting yield. Biomass is estimated in the field by destructive methods and sampling plants from a delimited area in the field (<span style=" color: #0070C0;">Yue et al., 2017</span>). Remote sensing and multispectral satellite data allow biomass to be evaluated in large applications, economically and in a very short time. Research has shown that estimating above ground biomass accumulation using remote sensing and vegetation indices is achievable with satisfactory accuracy (<span style=" color: #0070C0;">Ajaere, 2012</span>; <span style=" color: #0070C0;">Wang et al., 2016</span>).</p><p class="s29" style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><span class="s15">Kross et al. (2015) </span><span class="p">proposed transfer functions for biomass that use as an independent variable the </span>accumulated NDVI (NDVI<span class="s30">cumulative</span>) throughout the growing season. The general type of a transfer <span class="p">function is as follows:</span></p><p class="s18" style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 7pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 12pt;text-align: justify;">Biomass <span class="s19"></span><span class="s20"> </span>a<span class="s19"></span>x<span class="s31">b</span></p><p class="s18" style="padding-left: 7pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 12pt;text-align: justify;">Biomass <span class="s19"></span><span class="s20"> </span>a <span class="s19"></span><span class="s20"> </span>b <span class="s19"></span><span class="s20"> </span>x</p><p class="s29" style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">where x is the NDVI<span class="s30">cumulative </span>, a and b are fitting parameters. To build a robust biomass transfer function, <span class="p">datasets of measured in-situ biomass and plant spectral reflectance on the day of the measurement, are required. According to the methodology proposed by </span><span class="s15">Kross et al. (2015)</span><span class="p">, the cumulative NDVI is calculated by computing the area under the curve defined by the sensed NDVI in different time periods.</span></p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-top: 5pt;padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">It is estimated that a minimum of 19 satellite images (datasets of NDVI) will be acquired during the growing season of an annual crop, considering the Sentinel-2 revisit times. However, NDVI values are not expected to be distributed equally per month, due to cloud cover.</p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a href="#bookmark51" class="s5">In the CMS Service, the crop-specific biomass is calculated for five crops, namely wheat, maize, cotton, soybean and sunflower. Crop biomass values (in Mg/ha ≡ tn/ha) are provided per pixel with a spatial resolution of 10 m. The transfer functions for the calculation of biomass are provided in </a>Table 3.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p class="s21" style="padding-left: 15pt;text-indent: style="width:109pt;border-top-style:solid;border-top-width:1pt;border-top-color:#A7A8A7;border-left-style:solid;border-left-width:1pt;border-left-color:#A7A8A7;border-bottom-style:solid;border-bottom-width:1pt;border-bottom-color:#A7A8A7;border-right-style:solid;border-right-width:1pt;border-right-color:#A7A8A7"><p class="s23" style="padding-left: 98pt;padding-right: 98pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 9pt;text-align: center;">𝐵𝑖𝑜𝑚𝑎𝑠𝑠 = −214.8 + 19.2 ⋅ 𝑁𝐷𝑉𝐼<span class="s25">𝑐𝑢𝑚𝑢𝑙𝑎𝑡𝑖𝑣𝑒</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h3 style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark14">Requirements for the algorithm selection and design</a><a name="bookmark52">&zwnj;</a></h3><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">The Bottom-Of-Atmosphere (BOA) reflectance Sentinel-2 L-2A images will be used to derive the VIs required for the calculation of biophysical parameters. The Sentinel-2 L-2A products are atmospherically, terrain and cirrus corrected and will be acquired through the AWS API (Amazon Web Services Application Programming Interface) gateway. The resulting Sentinel-2 L-2A datasets contain several layers of information, including data from the on-board MSI sensor (13 bands, 443 nm – 2190 nm wavelengths, 10 – 60 m spatial resolution), as well as information over the cloud coverage, water presence, thin cirrus presence, etc. A Scene Classification Map (SCL) at 20 m resolution is included in the L-2A datasets together with Quality Indicators for cloud and snow probabilities. The SCL layer consists of four different classes for clouds (including cirrus) and six different classifications (shadows, cloud shadows, vegetation, soils/deserts, water and snow) (<span style=" color: #0070C0;">ESA, 2015</span>).</p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">The AWS API provides a vector file for each product that depicts the cloud boundaries. By using the information in this file and cross-referencing it with the boundaries of a registered parcel, the system identifies the cloud-free version product and proceeds to the download. No preprocessing of the downloaded products, as well as re-projection are required. The final steps of data processing involve removing any clouds in the image (if they exist) and then crop the entire tile and serve back only a small image, that of the registered parcel. In short, the steps that are involved in this process are the following:</p></li><li data-list-text=""><p style="padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: -18pt;line-height: 11pt;text-align: left;">create a shapefile (.shp) of the downloaded file from Amazon (.gml);</p></li><li data-list-text=""><p style="padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: -18pt;line-height: 11pt;text-align: left;">mask the EO data with the shapefile, essentially cutting “holes” where the clouds existed;</p></li><li data-list-text=""><p style="padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: -18pt;line-height: 11pt;text-align: left;">crop the image into the desired extent (parcel or area of interest);</p></li><li data-list-text=""><p style="padding-left: 41pt;text-indent: -18pt;line-height: 11pt;text-align: left;">create a zip file of all the requested bands (images).</p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">Landsat-8 carries an Operational Land Imager (OLI) and a Thermal Infrared Sensor (TIRS) instrument on board. Surface reflectance data from Landsat-8 products are generated at 30 m spatial resolution UTM or Polar Stereographic (PS) mapping grid at GeoTIFF file format. Landsat8, launched in 2012, acquires images with 11 spectral bands; it has a revisit time of 16 days. The CMS Service exploits Landsat-8 optical data synergistically with Sentinel-2. Specifically, six bands (visible, NIR and SWIR) are being used with 30 m spatial resolution. Landsat-8 optical data are already atmospherically corrected and projected. Thus, no preprocessing of the downloaded products as well as reprojection will be performed, apart from cropping into the desired extent (parcel or area of interest).</p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">A VI can be defined as the derivative of reflectance with respect to wavelength, which is an indicator of the abundance and activity of absorbers in the canopy (<span style=" color: #0070C0;">Myneni et al., 1995</span><a href="#bookmark53" class="s5">). There is a number of VIs, published in scientific literature and used in practice, developed as the combination of various wavebands and related to various canopy parameters. Their purpose is to enhance the vegetation signal and minimize soil background effects. VIs can be used as proxy to some characteristics of vegetation or as input in the models for estimation of biophysical properties of vegetation. The equations used to derive the VIs used in CMS Service for the calculation of crop biophysical parameters are provided in Table </a>4, along with the multispectral bands of the Sentinel-2 satellite used in each of them and the spatial resolution.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"/><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"/><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"/><h3 style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark15">Algorithm Outline/Flow Chart</a><a name="bookmark54">&zwnj;</a></h3><p style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a href="#bookmark55" class="s5">The NDVI processing routine involves the initial resampling of all image bands to the appropriate spatial resolution (10 m), and the spatial subset of the image to the area of interest envelope boundaries. At a further step the index is calculated with the use of the broadband NIR channel, and finally the NDVI layer is masked, rejecting pixels that are classified as clouds, cirrus or ice on the SCL layer. A chart with the NDVI processing workflow is presented in Figure </a>1. In a same way, all the vegetation indices are produced and biophysical parameters are derived.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><span><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><img width="616" height="215" src="data:image/jpg;base64,"/></td></tr></table></span></p><p class="s21" style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 15pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;"><a name="bookmark55">Figure 1. class="s11" style="padding-top: 3pt;padding-left: 7pt;padding-right: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;">AgroApps API</p></td><td style="width:106pt;border-top-style:solid;border-top-width:1pt;border-top-color:#A7A8A7;border-left-style:solid;border-left-width:1pt;border-left-color:#A7A8A7;border-bottom-style:solid;border-bottom-width:1pt;border-bottom-color:#A7A8A7;border-right-style:solid;border-right-width:1pt;border-right-color:#A7A8A7"><p class="s11" style="padding-top: 3pt;padding-left: 11pt;padding-right: 10pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: center;">Crop specific</p></td></tr></table><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h3 style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark20">Visualization of Output Data</a><a name="bookmark60">&zwnj;</a></h3><p style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;">Dropdown Menu in case more than one products per crop are selected by the external partner:</p><p style="padding-left: 70pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><span><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><img width="447" height="125" src="data:image/jpg;base64,"/></td></tr><tr><td><img width="447" height="125" 0pt;text-align: center;">Graph depicting the variation throughout the growing season</p><p style="padding-left: 89pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><span><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><img width="392" height="180" src="data:image/jpg;base64,"/></td></tr></table></span></p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h3 style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark21">Change Detection</a><a name="bookmark61">&zwnj;</a></h3><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">The CMS Service will also calculate differences between consecutive dates to ensure effective monitoring of the crop condition variability in both space and time. Push notification will be send to the external client informing for deviations and discrepancies between two successive images. This is accomplished through change detection between images, and specifically on NDVI. In order to apply NDVI image differencing for crop damage assessment, certain limitations must be considered. Initially, a time-series of images each having a cloud-free view of the area of interest – in this case, a parcel, must be acquired. The time series must capture both the pre- and the post- status of the crops. The temporal baseline between the two acquisitions should be as small as possible to decrease the influence of temporal distortions. Unlike urban areas, vegetated areas present high temporal distortions within a few days. In this case, the repeat cycle of the Sentinel-2 (or Landsat8) mission is the controlling key factor of the temporal baseline. The comparison will be applied in the two available satellite images pixel by pixel and an averaged ΔNDVI will be derived. The difference between the averaged NDVIs will be expressed in percent and provided as a push notification to the external user.</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><h2 style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark22">Micro-Service/NDVI Anomaly</a><a name="bookmark62">&zwnj;</a></h2><h3 style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark23">Role of the service/product</a><a name="bookmark63">&zwnj;</a></h3><p style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">The Moderate Resolution Imaging Spectroradiometer (MODIS) is one of the most widely used sensors in terms of drought monitoring (<span style=" color: #0070C0;">Rojas et al., 2011</span>). NDVI has been used to assess vegetation status in order to detect that greenness of vegetation canopy during the growing season, is affected by drought (<span style=" color: #0070C0;">Nanzad et al., 2019</span>).</p><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">The drought indicator NDVI Anomaly in <b>CMS Service </b>is calculated with the use of the GIMMS NDVI, GMOD09Q1 product obtained from 2001 onwards. These products are level-2G daily surface reflectance</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"><br/></p><p style="padding-top: 5pt;padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">gridded data in approximately 250 m spatial resolution in sinusoidal projection with a temporal resolution of 8 days (composites).</p><p style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">The MODIS data are downloaded, mosaicked and re-projected to geographic coordinates (datum WGS84). The images are cropped to the area of interest. MODIS NDVI data are collected throughout the growing season of a registered parcel. The historical NDVI datasets are downloaded from the National Aeronautics and Space Administration Earth Observing System Dataset and Information System (https://ladsweb.modaps. eosdis.nasa.gov) and are updated continuously with newly available NDVI data.</p><h3 style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark24">Literature on the service/product</a><a name="bookmark64">&zwnj;</a></h3><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">NDVI anomaly product is calculated to characterize the health of vegetation compared to what is considered normal and is used as an indicator of drought or declining vegetation health. A positive NDVI-Anomaly indicates enhanced vegetation conditions compared to the average, while a negative value indicates comparatively poor vegetation conditions (<span style=" color: #0070C0;">Anyamba et al., 2001</span>). The CMS Service calculates the NDVI Anomaly (NDVI-A) by subtracting the NDVI values for a particular date range from the historical average for the same date range. The historical average is based on the NDVI values of the corresponding 8-day period from 2001 until present. This approach is then used to characterize drought severity.</p><h3 style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark25">Algorithm description</a><a name="bookmark65">&zwnj;</a></h3><p style="padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">The 8-day NDVI-A is derived using the formula for each pixel of the registered parcel (<span style=" color: #0070C0;">Anyamba et al., 2001</span>), as follows:</p><p style="text-indent: 0pt;text-align: left;"/><p class="s43" style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 7pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 74%;text-align: justify;">NDVI <span class="s44"></span><span class="s45"> </span>A <span class="s44"></span><span class="s45"> </span><span class="s46">NDVI</span><span class="s47">current </span><span class="s48"></span><span class="s49"> </span><span class="s46">NDVI</span><span class="s47">mean </span><span class="s50"></span><span class="s51">100</span></p><p class="s52" style="padding-left: 85pt;text-indent: 0pt;line-height: 81%;text-align: left;">NDVI<span class="s53">mean</span></p><p class="s29" style="padding-top: 1pt;padding-left: 5pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">where NDVI-A is the NDVI anomaly for the current 8-day period of the growing season, NDVI<span class="s30">current </span>is the current MODIS NDVI 8-day composite and NDVI<span class="s30">mean </span>is the historical average for the same 8-day, <span class="p">from 2001 until present.</span></p><h3 style="padding-top: 2pt;padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark26">Requirements for the algorithm selection and design</a><a name="bookmark66">&zwnj;</a></h3><p style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">The CMS Service uses MODIS data for crop status and agricultural drought detection and monitoring. It utilizes the GIMMS NDVI GMOD09Q1 product (GIMMS MODIS Terra &amp; Aqua NDVI 8-bit 9x9 degree Tiles). The MODIS NDVI datasets are produced by the NASA/GSFC/GIMMS group for the USDA/FAS Global Agricultural Monitoring project. The NASA-GIMMS group provides satellite-derived vegetation products in two modes. A Near Real Time processing mode and a Scientific Quality standard mode. Forward near real-time (nrt) processing of this dataset is available within 12 hours from the last day of the 8-day composite period. Science quality, standard (std) processing is typically available one or more days after the last day of the 8-day composite period. The two processing modes differ in their ephemeris and production rules.</p><p style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">NDVI Anomaly supports operational land and crop condition monitoring requiring NDVI data composited in 8-day intervals and derived based on the historical average. NDVI Anomaly is the difference between the average NDVI for a particular month of a given year and the average NDVI for the same month over a specified number of years. The GMOD09Q1 product is processed starting with daily MODIS Terra surface reflectance data followed by a compositing process, not to average 8 days of data together, but instead to select the best observation for each pixel.</p><p style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">The MODIS NDVI datasets must be downloaded from 2001 until present. The most representative tiles corresponding to the registered parcels will be located and downloaded, per date of interest (e.g. the day a relevant product is expected to be uploaded by the providers) and then it will modify the data pool URL according to the needed criteria, in order to introduce the desired product in the automated workflow. The downloaded products do not require reprojection and will be cropped into the desired extent that will enclose all registered parcels.</p><h3 style="padding-top: 3pt;padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;"><a name="bookmark27">Algorithm Outline/Flow Chart</a><a name="bookmark67">&zwnj;</a></h3><p style="padding-left: 6pt;text-indent: 0pt;text-align: justify;">The drought severity classification scheme is adopted from the NDVI-A classification scheme, which includes mild drought, moderate drought, severe drought and a very severe drought in ascending order of severity (<span style=" color: #0070C0;">Legesse and Suryabhagavan, 2014</span>; <span style=" color: #0070C0;">Mutsotso et al., 2018</span><a href="#bookmark68" class="s5">).
